05767nam a22008535i 9780814708286DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780814708286  a(DE-B1597)547660  a(OCoLC)857769562  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF352b.M35 2016 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a349.7322300aMaking Legal History :bEssays in Honor of William E. Nelson /ced. by Daniel J. Hulsebosch, R. B. Bernstein. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tI. Civil Wars and Legal Rights -- t1. The Landscape of Faith -- t2. “It cant be cald stealin’” -- t3. Debating the Fourteenth Amendment -- tII. Law and Social Regulation -- t4. Was the Warning of Strangers Unique to Colonial New England? -- t5. Ambiguities of Free Labor Revisited -- t6. The Long, Broad, and Deep Civil Rights Movement -- t7. Counting as a Tool of Legal History -- tIII. Courts, Judges, and Litigators -- t8. A Mania for Accumulation -- t9. The Political Economy of Pain -- t10. An Unexpected Antagonist -- tBibliography of the Scholarship of William E. Nelson, 1963–2012 -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the academy’s leading legal historians, William E. Nelson is the Edward Weinfeld Professor of Law at New York University School of Law. For more than four decades, Nelson has produced some of the most original and creative work on American constitutional and legal history. His prize-winning books have blazed new trails for historians with their substantive arguments and the scope and depth of Nelson’s exploration of primary sources. Nelson was the first legal scholar to use early American county court records as sources of legal and social history, and his work (on legal history in England, colonial America, and New York) has been a model for generations of legal historians. This book collects ten essays exemplifying and explaining the process of identifying and interpreting archival sources-the foundation of an array of methods of writing American legal history. The essays presented here span the full range of American history from the colonial era to the 1980s.Each historian has either identified a body of sources not previously explored or devised a new method of interrogating sources already known.The result is a kaleidoscopic examination of the historian’s task and of the research methods and interpretative strategies that characterize the rich, complex field of American constitutional and legal history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLawxHistoryxUnited States. 0aLawzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aBarringer Gordon, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, R. B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBlumenthal, Susanna L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown-Nagin, Tomiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCushman, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDayton, Cornelia H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Daniel W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorwitz, Morton J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHulsebosch, Daniel J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMackey, Thomas C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalinger, Sharon V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela